[!INFO] Summary : read this
TRALI : development of ARDS with fever in a patient within 6 hours of transfusion of blood or blood products.
It's a febrile, non haemolytic transfusion reaction.
Occurs due to activation of recipient pumonary neutrophils by anti HLA antibodies present in donor serum.
Requires ventilatory support.
Usually self limiting in 2 to 4 days.

Transfusion related acute lung injury

  • A type of febrile non-haemolytic transfusion reaction - Medscape
  • Associated with mortality around 15% but much higher in critically ill patients.

Case vignette: A 65 year old man with myelodisplastic syndrome is receiving his regular transfusion and halfway through the transfusion, develops dyspnoea with desaturation and fever. - PassMedicine

[!INFO] Background physiology of neutrophil activation
Source
There is a disproportionately large number of neutrophils in the pulmonary circulation which defend body from pulmonary pathogens.Source
Immunoglobulins bind to neutrophils via an Fc - Fc receptors (on the neutrophil membrane) interaction.

Neutrophils kill pathogens in 3 ways


"During NETosis, DNA fibers decorated with histones and granular proteins, such as elastase and myeloperoxidase are released in structures known as neutrophil extracellular traps (NETs)."

Features:
TRALI occurs due to antineutrophil or anti-human leukocyte antigen (HLA) antibodies.

1. HLA class I or HLA class II **antibodies from the donor** react with lung neutrophils antigens in the recipient triggering inflammation.
  • Smokers, alcohol user, liver transplant
  • Occurs due to leukocyte antibodies from the donor; most commonly in multiparous female donors in whom maternal alloantibody formation occurred after exposure to paternally derived alloantigens on the fetal white blood cells entering the maternal circulation during pregnancy
  • Either way, the result is non cardiogenic pulmonary oedema. (i.e ARDS)
  • The recipient develops acute onset cough, SOB and fever and perihilar and lower zone shadowing in the CXR shortly after transfusion (within 6 hours).
  • Usually resolves in 2 to 4 days.
  • Can occur with FFP and platelets.
  • Measures to reduce TRALI incidence are avoidance of using female plasma and testing female donors for leukocyte antibodies.

TACO

Transfusion associated CIRCULATORY OVERLOAD

TACO is the most frequent pulmonary-related transfusion complication It is now the leading cause of transfusion-related fatalities in the USA.

TRALI and TACO are differentiated by the fact that

  • TRALI has hypotension and
  • TACO has hypertension.
  • Usually occurs within 3 months of drug use.

ALT and AST = hepatitis.
ALP and GGT = cholestatic.

Inhibition of RNA synthesis:

  • RIFAMPICIN
    • Vancomycin inhibits peptidoglycan synthesis, not peptidoglycan crosslinking like the beta lactam antibiotics do.

Succinylcholine and neuromuscular blockers

  • aka Suxamethonium (mnemonic: depolarization sux)
  • It is "ultra-short-acting". (half life 1 - 2 minutes, duration 5-6 minutes)
  • Suxamethonium is a non-competitive partial agonist.
  • It's made up of two ACh molecules bound together.
  • Side effects:
    • Tachycardia / bradycardia
    • Increased intracranial pressure
    • Hyperkalemia
    • Masseter spasm

Veruconium

  • Non depolarizing neuromuscular blocker.
  • Competitive inhibition of Ach binding to the receptor.
  • Reversed by neostigmine which is a reversible acetylcholinesterase inhibitor.
